<font color="#FF0000">THE REAL KOREAN WAR MEMORIAL</font><br>
<tt>Mon May  5 10:53:29 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Ken,<br><br>
I spent over a year in Korea, longer than I spent in Vietnam.  There is a bit of a difference between our involvement in the two countries.  I will tell more about Korea, and its legacy with me, later.  But now, I'd like to address your thoughts about a memorial, and maybe change your outlook a bit.  <br><br>
You guys did a hell of a grand job in Korea, one which shines into today and beyond.  The lives lost in Korea, the anguish and tears, the cold (yes, I know how cold it can get there) and the fears, were, and are, unquestionably, worth the price we paid.  <br><br>
You see, Ken (and all the other Korean War Vets) your memorial isn't confined to a small gash in the ground (which is as it is for a purpose) in Washington D.C.  Your memorial is a vibrant, thriving, wonderful country called South Korea, and its population of gracious, happy (for the most part) energetic, warm, hospitable people.  The South Korean people are self-sufficient, and very open to Americans.  They are also very appreciative of your and all the others' sacrifices for South Korea, for giving a whole people a chance to thrive.  <br><br>
Ken, if you wish to see your memorial, turn to pages 232 and 233 of the August 1988 issue of National Geographic Magazine, where evening traffic swirls around the old South Gate of the city of Seoul, where skyscrapers outline the city, and where the mechanical crane is the nations symbol.  <br><br>
Without what you guys did in the 1950's, none of this would be possible.  (The contrast, especially at this moment, between the two Koreas could not be more dramatic.) For this, I know that the South Korean People say to you and all the other Korean War Vets, Kum Sum Nee Da--Thank You.<br><br>
Ken, I don't know why I'm crying right now, but perhaps it is because the South Korean outcome is what we wished for South Vietnam.  
